in your office like this.

01:38.557 --> 01:40.343
- You didn’t have
to bring me coffee.
— The coffee’s mine.

01:40.434 --> 01:42.641
But I did print up some
apartment listings for you.
Take a look.

01:42.728 --> 01:45.765
This place is a mess, huh?
[Whistles ]

01:45.856 --> 01:48.768
Oh! I can’t believe
you gave Daisy the apartment.

01:48.859 --> 01:52.351
You know, I broke up with her.
I can’t take the apartment too.

01:52.446 --> 01:55.654
Come on! Man, look at you.
You gotta shake it off. Right?

01:55.741 --> 01:57.902
Get a new girlfriend.
Get a new place to live.

01:57.994 --> 02:00.280
Yeah, thanks.
I’ll check these out.

02:00.371 --> 02:03.283
You’ve been sleeping
in this office for two weeks.
You’re gonna go cuckoo.

02:03.374 --> 02:06.707
If anyone knows
what cuckoo is,
that would be you, Mr. Shrink.

02:06.794 --> 02:08.830
Maybe I’m dealing
with a few things
that are preventing me...

02:08.921 --> 02:10.377
from moving on
as quickly as I could.

02:10.506 --> 02:12.588
[Cell Phone Rings]
A breakup like this
makes one reevaluate—

02:12.675 --> 02:14.757
Oh— Oh. Work calls.

02:14.885 --> 02:17.922
Uh, the dead waits for no man.
Okay. That—

02:18.014 --> 02:20.596
Yeah, okay,
let’s get back to work.

02:22.393 --> 02:25.851
All right, I’ll tell you what,
Sweets. Why don’t you
just come and...

02:25.938 --> 02:27.894
stay at our place for,
like, a night or two?

02:28.024 --> 02:29.810
Really?
Yeah.

02:29.900 --> 02:33.609
So you can clear your mind,
you know. Get ready
for your next move.

02:33.696 --> 02:36.529
Thank you.
Clear my mind.

02:36.615 --> 02:40.073
Here, have a coffee.
You’re back. Come on.

02:41.037 --> 02:42.698
Let’s go, Sweets.
I’m coming.

02:42.788 --> 02:45.450
[Siren Wails]
[ People Chattering ]

02:45.541 --> 02:47.907
[ Police Rad/'0 Chatter]

02:55.343 --> 02:57.004
You invited Sweets
to move in with us?

02:57.136 --> 03:00.128
I know I should have asked you first,
but you should have seen him.
He was pitiful.

03:00.222 --> 03:04.135
I mean, it was bad. But it’s
just for a couple of days
until he finds his own place.

03:04.268 --> 03:08.056
Okay.
Was that an “okay” okay, or
“you can’t be serious” okay?

03:08.189 --> 03:11.477
I don’t know what that means.
It means that we’re talking
about Psychology Sweets here.

03:11.567 --> 03:13.023
You know, the guy
who drives you crazy.

03:13.110 --> 03:15.852
He’s going through a difficult time.
It takes a village, Booth.

03:15.946 --> 03:17.277
I learned that living in a village.

03:17.365 --> 03:19.481
Sweets will be gone
in a couple days.
I promise, okay?

03:19.575 --> 03:21.861
Gone? Gone where?
Is he okay?

03:21.952 --> 03:24.614
- Booth invited Sweets
to live with us.
— Not to live.

03:24.705 --> 03:28.038
To stay with us for a couple of days
until he finds his own place.

03:28.125 --> 03:29.956
Is he still dealing with
his breakup from Daisy?

03:30.044 --> 03:32.911
Yeah. I feel bad for the kid,
you know? lt’s— It’s tough.

03:33.005 --> 03:36.418
Aw. He’s going through
an early—life crisis.

03:36.550 --> 03:38.051
Good luck.
Good luck?

03:38.135 --> 03:39.841
I don’t need luck.
This is not about luck.

03:39.929 --> 03:42.716
This is about a friend
extending to another friend.

03:42.807 --> 03:44.593
It’s like an olive branch that— Stop.

03:44.683 --> 03:48.267
Can we just stop and deal
with this here? The remains.
What’s up with this?

03:48.354 --> 03:51.892
Based on the width
of the greater sciatic notch...

03:51.982 --> 03:55.941
and the dorsal margin
of the pubic face,
this was a female.

03:56.028 --> 03:58.485
Early to mid-20s.

03:58.572 --> 04:01.905
There’s no organs to examine,
so there’s nothing for me here.

04:01.992 --> 04:06.235
Ugh. Whoa. The Coch/I'omy/a
mace/lane eggs and larvae...

04:06.330 --> 04:10.869
measuring upwards of four
millimeters means our victim’s
been dead for about 36 hours.

04:10.960 --> 04:13.997
— Is that a foot?
- That is a foot. Hey, so, uh,

04:14.088 --> 04:17.000
Sweets told Angela that he was
never getting involved
with anyone again, so...

04:17.091 --> 04:19.924
— good luck with that.
— Let’s stop with
the luck stuff, okay?

04:20.010 --> 04:22.001
Can we just deal with what’s
going on in front of us?

04:22.096 --> 04:25.259
Okay, Bones, so it only took
a day and a half
to get down to bone?

04:25.349 --> 04:28.182
Heavy sharp—force trauma
indicates that tissue, muscle...

04:28.269 --> 04:30.009
and viscera have been ripped
from her bones.

04:30.104 --> 04:31.469
Where’s all the gutsy stuff?

04:31.564 --> 04:33.395
[Groans]
I think I might have found it.

04:34.650 --> 04:36.561
Yeah. Gutsy stuff.

04:37.278 --> 04:38.814
Whoa.

04:39.947 --> 04:41.107
[ Booth ]
Oh!

04:41.240 --> 04:42.229
There’s a leak.
Oh.

04:42.324 --> 04:43.359
No guts, no glory.

04:44.702 --> 04:46.283
Good luck with that.

04:46.370 --> 04:47.871
[Sighs]

05:26.911 --> 05:28.902
Numerous deep incisions
to the glabella,

05:28.996 --> 05:31.829
supraorbital ridges,
zygomatic arches—

05:31.916 --> 05:33.452
Her face was scratched off.

05:33.542 --> 05:36.500
thoracic and pelvic regions...

05:36.587 --> 05:37.952
and the extremities.

05:38.047 --> 05:40.584
Oh, my God.
This is awful.

05:40.674 --> 05:43.165
Yes. It will take
some time to catalog.

05:43.260 --> 05:46.093
Judging by the mass,
this has to be
almost all her flesh.

05:46.180 --> 05:49.513
With this many wounds,
there should be particulates
from the weapon on the bone.

05:49.600 --> 05:51.636
It’s gonna be difficult
to isolate cause of death.

05:51.727 --> 05:54.719
— It’ll be a doozy.
— Yes, a real doozy.

05:54.813 --> 05:58.476
We should get whatever flesh
is still on these bones removed.

05:58.567 --> 06:02.310
Okay, just please tell me that
this poor thing was dead...

06:02.404 --> 06:05.271
before any of this happened.

06:05.366 --> 06:07.072
- I’m sure she was.
— Definitely.

06:07.159 --> 06:09.150
Great.

06:10.788 --> 06:12.699
Hodgins and Cam
are lying to Angela...

06:12.790 --> 06:14.405
— to spare her feelings.
— Yeah, I got that.

06:14.500 --> 06:16.240
Because we have not
in any way ascertained...

06:16.335 --> 06:18.121
if the victim
was dead or alive...

06:18.212 --> 06:19.577
when she was
flayed to the bone.

06:19.672 --> 06:22.379
We have ascertained actually.

06:22.466 --> 06:24.752
Acute liver hemorrhaging suggests...

06:24.843 --> 06:27.585
that the victim was still alive...

06:27.680 --> 06:29.170
when she was eviscerated.

06:29.265 --> 06:32.348
— So I out—and—out lied to Angela.
- Thank you for that.

06:34.853 --> 06:38.311
What kind of monster guts his victim
and then removes all her flesh?

06:38.399 --> 06:41.516
In 1957, Ed Gein
was arrested for murder.

06:41.610 --> 06:44.727
And while searching his home,
police stumbled upon...

06:44.822 --> 06:48.280
bowls made of human skulls,
lampshades of human flesh,

06:48.367 --> 06:50.073
even a belt made out of nipples.

06:50.160 --> 06:51.991
The heinousness
of Gein’s crimes...

06:52.079 --> 06:54.786
diminishes in comparison
to those of the Aztecs.

06:54.873 --> 06:56.829
More heinous than a nipple belt?

06:56.917 --> 06:59.454
In order to appease Huehueteotl,
the fire god,

06:59.545 --> 07:03.083
the Aztecs would
burn their captives alive.

07:03.173 --> 07:06.882
Moments before death,
the human sacrifices
were pulled from the fire...

07:06.969 --> 07:09.585
to have their still—beating hearts
ripped out of their chests.

07:09.680 --> 07:12.217
- Those were the good old days.
- Those were the bad days.

07:12.308 --> 07:16.017
What— What kind of freak feels
nostalgic over human sacrifices?

07:16.103 --> 07:18.310
I’m gonna go ahead
and plead the Fifth on that.

07:18.397 --> 07:22.686
Severe chipping to the frontal,
nasal and zygomatic bones...

07:22.776 --> 07:25.233
prevents a complete facial
reconstruction.

07:25.321 --> 07:27.983
— Does that mean that Angela’s
off the hook for this one?
- Yes.

07:28.073 --> 07:30.029
- Yes!
— Um, actually—

07:30.117 --> 07:32.073
I hate to be the one
to suggest this,

07:32.161 --> 07:35.324
but Angela might be able
to reconstruct the face
from the face.

07:35.414 --> 07:37.996
You mean the face
from the skin, right?

07:38.083 --> 07:39.789
l have an ear,

07:39.877 --> 07:41.913
some cheek
and part of a nose.

07:42.004 --> 07:43.619
I’ll see what else
I can dig up.

07:43.714 --> 07:46.581
That is a very good idea, Cam.

07:46.675 --> 07:50.338
No need to tell Angela
that this was my
very good idea.

07:50.429 --> 07:51.544
Teamwork!

07:55.726 --> 07:57.182
[ Booth ]
So, you stay in here.

07:57.269 --> 08:00.181
Parker won’t be visiting us
for a couple months, so—

08:00.272 --> 08:01.978
Sorry about all the junk and toys.

08:02.066 --> 08:04.557
Oh, no. Beats the hell
out of my office.

08:04.652 --> 08:07.394
Look at all this stuff.
Kids from broken homes...

08:07.488 --> 08:08.978
really rake in
the material goods...

08:09.073 --> 08:11.405
by way of compensation.

08:12.451 --> 08:14.066
Right. Uh,
take a look at this.

08:14.203 --> 08:15.864
Take a closer look,
all right?
What?

08:15.954 --> 08:19.242
Oh, my God.
This corpse is so mutilated.

08:19.333 --> 08:22.496
Cut right down to the bone.
So you’re a psychologist. Who
would do something like this?

08:22.586 --> 08:24.087
Want me to figure
that out right now?

08:24.171 --> 08:27.379
No, I tell you what.
Why don’t you just relax.

08:27.466 --> 08:29.832
Make yourself at home. Huh?

08:29.927 --> 08:31.212
Take things in.
All right.

08:31.345 --> 08:33.256
Thanks.
Yep.

08:53.117 --> 08:56.530
This is the last piece
of facial tissue I found.

08:56.620 --> 08:59.657
Thank God. This is not
why I went to art school.

08:59.748 --> 09:02.330
I’ll start loading the images
into the computer,

09:02.418 --> 09:05.376
and I’ll piece them together,
and then I will hurl.

09:05.462 --> 09:08.420
Well, how long do you
think it’ll take you...

09:08.507 --> 09:10.247
to piece the pieces together?

09:10.342 --> 09:11.457
Oh, not long.

09:11.552 --> 09:13.713
I am starting a pool
on how long Sweets lasts...

09:13.804 --> 09:14.839
with Booth and Brennan.

09:14.930 --> 09:16.090
I say he’s out tonight.

09:16.181 --> 09:18.797
Did you swab the cuts
in the bones?
I did, yes.

09:18.892 --> 09:21.178
Yeah. So are you
in on the pool?

09:21.270 --> 09:23.477
I give Sweets four days.
What’d you find?

09:23.564 --> 09:25.520
Uh, ammonium hydroxide.
It’s the same stuff...

09:25.607 --> 09:27.268
that’s all over
our victim’s clothing.

09:27.359 --> 09:29.771
So, Angie, how long
do you give Sweets?

09:29.862 --> 09:33.150
[ Chuckles ]
I say he lives with them
permanently from now on.

09:33.240 --> 09:34.650
What’s ammonium hydroxide?

09:34.742 --> 09:36.482
It’s a cleaning product.

09:36.577 --> 09:40.115
- The killer probably used it
to wash away the evidence.
- Huh. Did it work?

09:40.205 --> 09:42.821
Yeah. It’s wiped out
all the other evidence
as far as I can see.

09:42.916 --> 09:45.578
[ Stammers ]
Wh—What do you mean
“from now on”?

09:45.669 --> 09:49.503
I mean for the foreseeable future.
They will adopt him.

09:50.549 --> 09:53.131
Well, I don’t have a box
for infinity.

09:53.218 --> 09:55.129
I mean, the furthest I went
was a month.

09:55.220 --> 09:56.596
Okay.
Then I’ll take the month.

09:56.680 --> 09:59.422
Our killer is sick and smart.
I hate that combination.

09:59.516 --> 10:03.429
Okay, so, this program will
search for wrinkles,

10:03.520 --> 10:06.762
freckles and other
microscopic facial features
on each piece,

10:06.857 --> 10:09.974
pick up the pattern,
and pair it with
the corresponding piece.

10:10.068 --> 10:12.775
— Very Frankensteiny.
— [ Saroyan ] Ew.

10:12.863 --> 10:17.698
Okay, so I’m gonna wrap
the face around the image
of the victim’s skull.

10:22.706 --> 10:24.537
Pop in eyeballs and hair.

10:26.752 --> 10:28.288
Okay. What do you think?

10:28.378 --> 10:30.994
That most definitely
looks like a human person.

10:31.131 --> 10:32.871
I know this woman.
You do?

10:32.966 --> 10:34.297
Oh, my God.

10:34.384 --> 10:36.420
Wh-What?
Is this a friend of yours?

10:36.512 --> 10:39.379
[ Hodgins ]
Not a friend but—
Whoa.

10:39.473 --> 10:42.761
Okay. This is Michael Vincent’s
favorite applesauce.

10:42.851 --> 10:45.228
And what does that have
to do with our victim?

10:48.065 --> 10:51.057
Someone killed
the Them Apples applesauce lady.

10:53.570 --> 10:56.528
Them Apples applesauce
is owned by the two girls
that are on the label,

10:56.615 --> 10:58.196
Jessica Pearson
and Brooke Guminski.

10:58.283 --> 11:00.820
[ Brennan ]
It’s the applesauce
I buy for Christine too.

11:00.911 --> 11:02.526
What the hell
is going on here?
Pumpkin butter.

11:02.621 --> 11:04.486
What is this, olden times?
[ Chuckles ]

11:04.581 --> 11:07.914
Olden times is not a legitimate
historical reference.

11:08.043 --> 11:10.284
But I see your point.
Right.

11:10.379 --> 11:12.586
[ Brennan ]
There’s a pickle maker
and a candlestick maker.

11:12.673 --> 11:15.164
Oh. I know
what this is.

11:15.259 --> 11:17.420
Okay. What is this,
a time portal?

11:17.553 --> 11:21.091
No, this is an artisanal
community, Booth.
Oh, that’s just ridiculous.

11:21.181 --> 11:24.969
From an anthropological
standpoint, the artisanal
subculture is fascinating.

11:25.060 --> 11:26.300
Really?
Fascinating?

11:26.436 --> 11:28.097
Well, to me,
I think it’s just stupid.
Hmm.

11:28.188 --> 11:30.930
The founding fathers
were heavily influenced
by the Athenians,

11:31.024 --> 11:32.639
which resulted
in democracy.
Care for a sample?

11:32.776 --> 11:34.141
So—
Uh, great.

11:34.278 --> 11:36.644
Democracy, Bones.
Not a pickle.
Enjoy your pickles.

11:36.780 --> 11:40.022
And if you want some more—
Creating handcrafted,
handmade products...

11:40.117 --> 11:42.984
provides artisans
with the authenticity
they feel is lacking...

11:43.078 --> 11:45.865
in today’s technology-driven,
industrialized world.

11:45.956 --> 11:47.696
Great. Okay, eat your pickle.
We’re here.

11:47.833 --> 11:49.494
These are very good.
You should have eaten yours.
That’s nice.

11:49.585 --> 11:51.075
I don’t want a pickle.

11:55.007 --> 12:00.172
In the 1930s, Joseph Ball
killed over 20 women and fed
their remains to alligators.

12:00.304 --> 12:02.295
Was this victim
fed to alligators?
I don’t think so.

12:02.389 --> 12:04.175
Please shut up
about alligators.

12:07.269 --> 12:10.887
Hemorrhagic staining indicates
these wounds were made
around time of death.

12:10.981 --> 12:15.975
The dimension of the “V”—shaped
incisions suggests the weapon
used to create them was a blade.

12:16.069 --> 12:18.105
Those are some
seriously deep cuts.

12:18.196 --> 12:20.653
Which only a serrated blade
should be capable of making,

12:20.741 --> 12:24.654
but I’m not finding any evidence
of striations in these wounds.

12:24.745 --> 12:28.863
- Meaning?
— Whoever did this
is incredibly strong.

12:33.420 --> 12:35.126
[ Booth ]
You okay? Is there someone
we should call?

12:35.213 --> 12:37.590
Usually, I’d say Jess.

12:37.674 --> 12:40.006
We ran this place together.

12:40.093 --> 12:43.005
- I can’t believe she’s dead.
— She is most certainly dead.

12:45.015 --> 12:46.755
Very sorry for your loss.

12:46.850 --> 12:48.215
[ Sniffles ]

12:48.310 --> 12:50.175
When was the last time
you saw your partner?

12:50.270 --> 12:52.602
Saturday afternoon.

12:52.689 --> 12:55.146
We had a pretty good morning
at the farmers’ market.

12:55.233 --> 12:58.361
We had lunch.
I dropped her off
at the free clinic.

12:59.529 --> 13:00.939
Wow.
She was my best friend.

13:01.031 --> 13:04.194
You charge nine dollars
for a jar of applesauce?

13:04.284 --> 13:05.615
Yes.

13:05.744 --> 13:07.826
You pay nine bucks
for this stuff?
Yes.

13:07.913 --> 13:12.498
Every apple is handpicked
from local orchards.
No chemicals, no additives.

13:12.584 --> 13:15.872
You think somebody killed Jess
because we charge nine dollars
for applesauce?

13:18.215 --> 13:23.130
Uh, so, um, what was
the purpose for her going
to the, uh, free clinic?

13:23.220 --> 13:25.176
Jess had lupus.

13:25.263 --> 13:27.845
She went in for her monthly
checkup before starting
a sales tour.

13:27.933 --> 13:31.391
She was gonna cover every
farmers’ market in Maryland,
starting with Baltimore.

13:33.063 --> 13:35.270
We were just starting
to make a go of this.

13:35.357 --> 13:38.190
Can you think of anyone
who would want
to hurt your partner?

13:40.195 --> 13:42.186
— Maybe.
- Maybe?

13:42.280 --> 13:43.895
There’s this creep, Adam.

13:43.991 --> 13:46.858
— He’s been getting kind of
stalkery with Jess lately.
— Stalkery how?

13:46.952 --> 13:48.533
Kept bringing her meat.

13:48.620 --> 13:50.360
Meat? No, that’s
definitely not normal.

13:50.455 --> 13:52.787
Oh, no— yeah.
Adam is a butcher.

13:52.874 --> 13:56.082
He’s creepy,
but he’s the butcher
down the street.

13:58.005 --> 14:00.587
Yeah, I’m Adam.
What do you want?

14:08.974 --> 14:13.593
Okay, Adam, F.B.|., all right?
Let’s put the cleaver down.
Have to ask you a few questions.

14:13.687 --> 14:15.894
Here we go again.

14:15.981 --> 14:20.645
You know, my shop is safer
than any regulations
that agribusiness paid for.

14:20.736 --> 14:22.692
l source all my meat locally,
all grass fed.

14:22.779 --> 14:25.691
- No hormones of any kind.
- Hey, pal, I don’t care
about your meat.

14:25.782 --> 14:28.694
We just have to ask you
a few questions about the death
of Jessica Pearson.

14:28.785 --> 14:31.037
Death?
What are you talking about?

14:31.121 --> 14:34.454
Ms. Pearson’s mutilated remains
were found in a garbage can...

14:34.541 --> 14:36.873
a quarter of a mile from here.

14:36.960 --> 14:40.919
Oh, my God. That’s horrible.
Wh—What happened?

14:41.006 --> 14:45.340
Our evidence indicates that
the murder was committed by
an exceptionally strong man...

14:45.427 --> 14:48.885
skilled at using
an extremely sharp knife.

14:48.972 --> 14:50.473
You think / killed Jessica?

14:50.557 --> 14:53.640
- Well, we know you were
trying to romance her.
- With free meat.

14:53.727 --> 14:56.514
Look, Jessica could
barely afford food.

14:56.605 --> 14:59.597
Every dime of hers went
into her business. l was
just trying to help her out.

14:59.691 --> 15:01.227
For what in return?

15:01.318 --> 15:03.274
Nothing.

15:03.361 --> 15:06.148
Especially after this guy
came in and threatened me.

15:06.281 --> 15:11.071
— What guy?
- I don’t know.
Some big—ass, angry—looking guy...

15:11.161 --> 15:14.995
threatened to crush my skull
like a cracker if I didn’t lay off Jess.

15:15.082 --> 15:19.496
Adam, do you rub ammonia
on your meat as a way
of killing bacteria?

15:19.586 --> 15:23.420
This is an artisan butchery.
I’d never use chemicals.

15:23.507 --> 15:25.168
Look, you can accuse me
of murder,

15:25.258 --> 15:29.171
but when you start
insulting my craft,
that’s where I draw the line.

15:29.262 --> 15:30.843
Good to know your priorities.

15:30.931 --> 15:34.298
We need to examine your knives
as possible murder weapons.

15:35.519 --> 15:38.056
You want my knives?
Get a warrant.

15:51.076 --> 15:52.737
You find any more money
in her clothes?

15:52.828 --> 15:54.864
Yep. It was mixed up
in the garbage.

15:54.955 --> 15:57.742
Oh, yeah. The smell
was a dead giveaway.

15:57.833 --> 16:00.074
Let’s see what we got.

16:09.344 --> 16:14.134
So, we found 20
hundred—dollar bills
on the victim.

16:14.224 --> 16:16.806
That’s a lot of money for a girl
who can barely afford to eat.

16:16.893 --> 16:19.145
Well, Brennan said
that the victim was
at a farmers’ market...

16:19.229 --> 16:21.060
selling her applesauce
the morning before she died.

16:21.148 --> 16:22.638
Maybe that’s where
she got the money.

16:22.732 --> 16:25.439
No, I don’t think so.
Look at this.

16:25.527 --> 16:27.233
The bills are sequential.

16:27.320 --> 16:29.936
[ Hodgins ]
Meaning that they came
from the same source.

16:30.031 --> 16:33.569
We love our kid, but we’re not
spending two grand a month on
applesauce at a farmers’ market.

16:33.660 --> 16:36.743
[ Sighs ]
What is she doing
with all this cash?

16:36.830 --> 16:40.618
And why was she making
monthly trips to the doctor
for blood tests?

16:40.709 --> 16:42.574
Her partner said
that she had lupus.

16:42.669 --> 16:44.034
I know, but she didn’t.

16:44.129 --> 16:47.496
I tested all the tissue.
Our victim was perfectly healthy.

16:47.591 --> 16:50.128
She was lying to her partner,
but the question is why.

16:50.218 --> 16:54.678
Regular doctor visits
for no reason,
a wad of cash.

16:54.764 --> 16:56.300
You think she was selling pills?

17:00.395 --> 17:01.726
[ Fussing ]
Want more?

17:01.813 --> 17:04.054
Aw. Booth is upset
that I pay...

17:04.149 --> 17:06.185
nine dollars a jar
for Christine’s applesauce.

17:06.276 --> 17:08.892
Well, artisanal products are
more expensive to produce,

17:08.987 --> 17:10.352
so they’re more expensive
to purchase.

17:10.447 --> 17:13.029
But the real value
comes in knowing
that they’re not made...

17:13.116 --> 17:15.823
by some faceless,
soul—destroying corporation.

17:15.911 --> 17:19.119
You seem to have a real
appreciation for the artisan,
Sweets.

17:19.206 --> 17:20.912
| used to work in a record shop.

17:22.792 --> 17:25.920
I’m afraid Christine will
never know what a record is.

17:26.004 --> 17:28.165
[ Sweets ]
Digital will never
replace vinyl.

17:29.424 --> 17:32.962
Hey there, you three. Huh?
Let’s go, Sweets.

17:33.053 --> 17:35.760
— Booth, Sweets was going
to get a hotel room.
— Hotels are nice.

17:35.847 --> 17:38.714
— Yeah, I’ll be fine.
— No, if you stay at a hotel,

17:38.808 --> 17:40.969
you will feel rushed
and you’ll take an apartment...

17:41.061 --> 17:43.677
that does not align
with your sensibilities.

17:43.772 --> 17:45.262
Wait a second.
Sweets has sensibilities?

17:45.357 --> 17:47.188
Yes. He worked
in a record shop.

17:48.318 --> 17:50.058
— So?
— I think what
Dr. Brennan means...

17:50.153 --> 17:53.771
is that working in a moribund enterprise
gave me a lasting appreciation...

17:53.865 --> 17:56.242
for the craftsmanship
that goes into making a record.

17:56.326 --> 17:59.159
You know, I remember stocking
this T. Rex album.

17:59.246 --> 18:03.034
Uh, the one with “20th Century Boy.”
And the liner notes, the album art,

18:03.124 --> 18:04.910
even the tactile feel of the vinyl—

18:05.001 --> 18:08.493
— And so you need an apartment
that tickles your same fancy.
- Yeah.

18:08.588 --> 18:12.080
Whoa, whoa. Excuse me.
Those are my underwear, pal.
What is he doing?

18:12.175 --> 18:15.133
Sweets has been very helpful.
He vacuumed, did the laundry.

18:15.220 --> 18:18.678
All right, that’s great and all,
but a man doesn’t fold
another man’s underwear.

18:18.765 --> 18:20.346
Are those
Captain America boxers?

18:20.433 --> 18:23.266
[ Brennan ]
Booth has
a nostalgic side too.

18:23.353 --> 18:27.141
You know, psychologically,
we yearn for our past
because we fear our future.

18:27.232 --> 18:32.147
Or you just like Captain America
or old records or your own
apartment. So can we go now?

18:32.237 --> 18:34.444
Come on, we have a doctor
to talk to.

18:34.531 --> 18:36.396
Let’s go. Thanks.
Thanks for that.

18:36.533 --> 18:38.990
Appreciate it.
I’m sorry.

18:39.995 --> 18:41.860
Okay.

18:47.168 --> 18:50.035
I saw Jessica at the clinic
just last Saturday.
Is she okay?

18:50.171 --> 18:53.663
Jessica was murdered
last Saturday evening.
Oh, my God.

18:56.469 --> 18:58.460
Was, uh, Jessica healthy,
Dr. Reese?

18:58.555 --> 19:00.762
Yes. Very. Why?

19:00.849 --> 19:02.714
Why did she come visit you
every month?

19:02.809 --> 19:04.891
Well, that’s confidential
information. Thank you.

19:04.978 --> 19:06.934
Not when your patient’s
been murdered.

19:07.022 --> 19:10.480
We found a lot of cash on her,
so we’re thinking maybe the two
of you were selling drugs.

19:10.567 --> 19:12.023
That’s absurd.

19:12.110 --> 19:14.226
You wouldn’t be
the first doctor...

19:14.321 --> 19:16.812
to make a little extra cash
distributing pills on the street.

19:16.948 --> 19:19.439
Jessica needed money.
That isn’t why she had
an appointment every month.

19:20.410 --> 19:21.866
[ Clears Throat]

19:21.953 --> 19:23.534
l have to tell you, legally?

19:23.621 --> 19:24.872
I’m afraid so.

19:24.956 --> 19:27.538
I don’t want you to get
the wrong impression of Jessica.

19:28.418 --> 19:29.954
Okay. Well, try us.

19:30.045 --> 19:32.582
Jessica came to the clinic
once a month...

19:32.672 --> 19:34.708
to have her blood tested
for S.T.D.’s.

19:34.799 --> 19:37.256
S.T.D.’s, cash—
Jessica was a prostitute?

19:37.344 --> 19:40.086
It’s not myjob
to tell my patients
how to live their lives.

19:40.180 --> 19:42.262
| just want them
to stay healthy.

19:48.438 --> 19:50.019
[ Saroyan ]
Pig bones?
[ Fisher] Yes.

19:50.106 --> 19:54.395
And I believe Dr. Brennan
will heap praise on me
for acquiring them.

19:54.527 --> 19:57.360
Not as if that
will cheer me up.
And why?

19:57.447 --> 20:00.905
’Cause I got ’em
from Adam Borchardt.
From his butchery.

20:00.992 --> 20:03.483
— The suspect?
— It’s a lot easier than waiting...

20:03.578 --> 20:05.694
for a warrant
that might never come.

20:05.789 --> 20:07.871
I figured if our butcher
butchered the victim,

20:07.957 --> 20:10.949
he might have done it
in a similar manner in which
he would butcher an animal.

20:11.044 --> 20:13.535
/ might have to heap
a little praise on you too.

20:13.630 --> 20:14.995
It would be wasted.

20:15.090 --> 20:17.627
Look at the cuts
on our victim’s bones.

20:17.717 --> 20:20.333
Each one extremely
precise and clean.

20:20.428 --> 20:23.420
No clefts, no hesitation marks.

20:23.515 --> 20:25.847
Definitely made by someone
who knows what they’re doing.

20:25.934 --> 20:27.925
Like the butchered pig bones.

20:28.019 --> 20:31.477
And the flesh was removed
in a similar way
as our victim’s.

20:31.564 --> 20:34.351
Is it true that she was
a lady of the night?

20:34.442 --> 20:38.105
According to Booth, she may have
been prostituting herself...

20:38.196 --> 20:39.982
as a way of supplementing
her income.

20:40.073 --> 20:43.031
An occasional prostitute.
Interesting.

20:43.118 --> 20:44.949
I was thinking sad.

20:45.036 --> 20:49.154
The nicks on both sides
of the mandible appear to be
at the ends of an arc...

20:49.249 --> 20:52.537
that would’ve transected
the victim’s left—side
carotid artery.

20:52.627 --> 20:54.492
The killer slit her throat.

20:54.587 --> 20:56.418
Judging by
the microscopic spalls,

20:56.506 --> 20:59.794
the nick on the right side
of the mandible would be
the exit wound.

20:59.884 --> 21:02.091
Meaning the killer
was right—handed.

21:02.178 --> 21:04.715
Which rules out
our left—handed butcher.

21:04.806 --> 21:06.637
I don’t look so good now,
do I?

21:06.724 --> 21:09.887
— Does that cheer you up?
- A little.

21:12.439 --> 21:13.895
Oh, my God.

21:15.442 --> 21:17.103
The killer slit her throat.

21:17.193 --> 21:19.855
That’s now old news.

21:19.946 --> 21:22.904
And she was an occasional
prostitute that was dumped
in the garbage.

21:22.991 --> 21:26.654
There is more than
butchery and applesauce
that’s old—school here.

21:28.580 --> 21:31.196
The killer is mimicking
Jack the Ripper.

21:57.442 --> 21:59.683
Do I even want to know?

21:59.777 --> 22:03.019
Dr. Saroyan. It’s past 10:00.
What are you still doing here?

22:03.114 --> 22:07.027
Oh, digging through
the booze—soaked lobster ravioli
I found in the victim’s stomach.

22:07.118 --> 22:09.109
Last meal, huh?

22:09.204 --> 22:12.662
2,000-buck-a-night call girl—
definitely not skimping on dinner.

22:12.749 --> 22:15.115
You might be able to find
what restaurant she went to.

22:15.210 --> 22:16.450
Your turn.

22:16.544 --> 22:19.456
I am examining
the victim’s remains.

22:19.547 --> 22:21.503
By the light of a lantern?

22:21.591 --> 22:23.456
Oh, the lantern provides
oblique lighting,

22:23.551 --> 22:26.759
which bounces off
an angled reflector
and back onto the bone,

22:26.846 --> 22:31.089
which happens to be awesome
for spotting scratches
and micro cuts on bone.

22:31.184 --> 22:34.017
But mostly it’s because
it appeals to your sense
of the macabre.

22:34.103 --> 22:36.435
[ Sighs ]
It does make me look insane,
doesn’t it?

22:36.523 --> 22:39.060
- Yes.
- Yeah.

22:39.150 --> 22:42.062
But what if I told you
I found something?

22:45.573 --> 22:49.486
Microfracturing on
the anterior aspect
of the right radius and ulna...

22:49.577 --> 22:51.909
is inconsistent
with the “V”—shaped incisions.

22:51.996 --> 22:54.203
So, not caused by a blade.

22:54.290 --> 22:55.541
Nope.

22:55.625 --> 22:57.115
What do you think
caused them?

22:57.210 --> 23:00.293
Well, I do not know,
but I can certainly
keep looking.

23:03.299 --> 23:06.632
And people think I’m creepy
because I’m a pathologist.

23:15.853 --> 23:17.639
[ Footsteps Approaching ]

23:18.273 --> 23:20.355
- Bones.
- Yes?

23:20.441 --> 23:21.851
ls Sweets in our bathroom?

23:21.943 --> 23:24.059
Yes. Should I have put
a note on the door?

23:24.153 --> 23:27.361
Well, a little warning.
That would have been nice.
What’s he doing in our bathtub?

23:27.448 --> 23:31.236
— Jets.
— Ourjets in our bathtub.

23:31.327 --> 23:35.946
Societies in Japan and Turkey
encourage public bathing.

23:36.040 --> 23:39.828
— In modern—day Finland—
— Finland? Whoa, whoa!
This is not Finland.

23:39.919 --> 23:42.080
[ Sighs ]
Sorry, Booth. I should
have locked the door, huh?

23:42.171 --> 23:46.505
Because you played on so many
sports teams and spent a lot
of time in the army,

23:46.593 --> 23:48.959
I assumed you were comfortable
with male nudity.

23:49.053 --> 23:51.089
You know, fear of nudity
is called gymnophobia?

23:51.180 --> 23:52.795
Okay, listen,
Psychology and Anthropology,

23:52.890 --> 23:55.017
I liked it better when you two
were fighting, all right?

23:55.101 --> 23:56.932
Are we done
with our bathtub?

23:57.061 --> 23:58.471
Yeah. Yeah.
Yeah.

23:58.563 --> 24:01.771
— I like to soak in our tub after work.
— [ Chuckles ]

24:01.858 --> 24:04.270
If you’d seen Booth’s X—rays,
you’d understand.

24:04.360 --> 24:08.478
The list of bones that he hasn’t broken
is shorter than the ones that he has.

24:08.615 --> 24:09.604
Reall ?
[ Knocking ] y-

24:09.699 --> 24:11.189
Now what?

24:11.701 --> 24:13.191
Yeah?

24:13.286 --> 24:15.527
— Hey, is Dr. Brennan home?
- What the hell
are you doing here?

24:15.622 --> 24:17.453
Sweets, looking right up
your skirt there.

24:17.540 --> 24:19.531
We weren’t expecting guests.

24:19.626 --> 24:21.457
[ Booth ]
We’re not expecting—
What are you do— Hello?

24:21.544 --> 24:23.455
Time out. Can this not
wait until tomorrow?

24:23.546 --> 24:27.004
Okay, check this out.
Microfracturing on both wrists.
Very symmetrical.

24:27.091 --> 24:29.082
The victim was restrained.

24:29.177 --> 24:31.589
This is looking more and more
like an abduction—torture scenario.

24:31.679 --> 24:33.294
This can’t wait
until tomorrow because?

24:33.389 --> 24:36.222
This probably isn’t
a one—time thing.
We have a serial killer!

24:36.309 --> 24:38.641
That’s what I’m saying.
Jack the Ripper is back.

24:38.728 --> 24:41.686
— Jack the Ripper.
I don’t buy it.
- Why?

24:41.773 --> 24:45.140
Because serial killers don’t
dump their victims in garbage.
Let’s go. Out!

24:45.234 --> 24:47.816
Out. Get out of the house.
Bye—bye. Done.

24:47.904 --> 24:51.396
Back to the lab, squint.
And you, Sweets,
go put some clothes on.

24:51.491 --> 24:54.824
Oy! [Whispering] Now I
have to go clean the tub.
[ Full Voice ] Thanks to Sweets.

24:54.952 --> 24:57.864
What did I do?
You don’t need to clean it.
[ Muttering ]

24:57.997 --> 24:59.908
Just get up the stairs,
Sweets.
What am I, a Sasquatch?

24:59.999 --> 25:00.749
Yes.

25:05.922 --> 25:07.503
[Angela ]
This artisan world.

25:07.590 --> 25:11.924
That’s why I studied art
in the first place—
to pursue my true passion.

25:12.011 --> 25:14.548
Hey, I thought I was
your true passion.

25:14.639 --> 25:16.129
[ Sighs ]
Good God.

25:17.600 --> 25:19.807
You know what I mean.
Yes, I do.

25:19.894 --> 25:22.180
My true passion
are bugs and slime,
and yours is art.

25:22.271 --> 25:24.182
But come on now,
I think we’re doing pretty well.

25:24.273 --> 25:28.437
Dr. Hodgins, what does
an ethanol composed of
rye, juniper berries...

25:28.528 --> 25:30.359
and licorice mean to you?

25:30.446 --> 25:33.688
Juniper berries and rye
points to gin.
Licorice—

25:33.783 --> 25:36.320
Is it part of the liquor
or—or separate?

25:36.411 --> 25:39.778
In the liquor. It was
the last thing our victim drank
before she was murdered.

25:39.914 --> 25:43.452
Was there a sign of any drugs?
Rohypnol? Narcotics?
No.

25:43.543 --> 25:47.081
Well, hey, gin can be pretty
debilitating all on its own.

25:47.171 --> 25:48.786
But she didn’t drink
all that much.

25:48.881 --> 25:51.588
Well, you’d think a prostitute
would deaden the pain...

25:51.676 --> 25:53.166
with anything she could find.

25:53.261 --> 25:56.173
[ Sighs ]
I hope someone isn’t
targeting prostitutes.

25:56.264 --> 25:59.802
It would help if we could talk
to the pimp, but Booth’s had
a hard time tracking him down.

25:59.892 --> 26:02.599
- Old Tom Gin.
— Excuse me?

26:02.687 --> 26:07.226
Old Tom Gin is an old—fashioned
English gin sweetened with
licorice instead of sugar.

26:07.316 --> 26:08.977
It’s extremely rare today.

26:09.068 --> 26:12.231
— [ Saroyan ]
It sounds like more artisans.
— Yeah, Cam is right.

26:12.363 --> 26:16.447
Old Tom Gin is made at
Dr. Biltmore’s micro distillery.
[Typing I

26:16.534 --> 26:20.368
Which is a few blocks from
our victim’s applesauce store.

26:21.247 --> 26:24.205
— And, oh, boy.
— What?

26:24.292 --> 26:28.410
Dr. Biltmore’s is owned
and operated by Dr. Cole Reese.

26:28.504 --> 26:30.836
The doctor that treated
our victim.

26:31.716 --> 26:33.877
Maybe it’s a coincidence.

26:33.968 --> 26:35.333
Sure.

26:42.685 --> 26:45.472
Reese had his own practice,
but closed it to open up
the distillery.

26:45.563 --> 26:47.394
So, uh, he volunteers
at the free clinic.

26:47.482 --> 26:49.347
These people all seem to be
following their dreams.

26:49.442 --> 26:50.932
Reese is following something,
all right.

26:51.027 --> 26:53.018
Look, read his record.

26:54.572 --> 26:57.860
Right. Arrested for solicitation in 2003.

26:57.950 --> 27:01.238
You know, one of the most
prevalent theories about
Jack the Ripper...

27:01.329 --> 27:03.911
is that he was, in fact,
a physician.

27:03.998 --> 27:06.580
The clinic would be an ideal way
to pick victims.

27:06.667 --> 27:09.204
Right, and to ensure
that the victim
wasn’t an undercover cop.

27:09.337 --> 27:10.622
Hmm?
That too.

27:10.713 --> 27:11.418
Yep.

